<h2 id="Strategy-Selection">Strategy Selection<a class="anchor-link" href="#Strategy-Selection">¶</a></h2><p>MC has number of strategies to select. Which one to select?</p>
<p><img alt="mc_2.gif" src="data:image/gif;base64, "/></p>
<p>It may select based on largely 3 criteria, and whichever in that is most important,</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>What related knowledge</strong> does it have specific to the problem? For ex, if for a problem, the cases are not avialbale, then CBR is not a choice </li>
<li><strong>Computational efficiency</strong> some choices may be more efficient. If a problem is very close to a case in past then CBR might be a good choice. </li>
<li><strong>Quality of solution</strong> Some comes with a guarantee (a quality) of solutions. For eg, <code>logic</code>. </li>
</ul>
<p>Similarly for learning methods,</p>
<p><img alt="2019-07-24_08h59_18.png" src="data:image/png;base64, "/></p>
<ul>
<li>Some may be applicable to the problem, and some may not. For exm, if examples come, one at a time, then ICP. </li>
<li>Computational efficiency and Quality of solutions like earlier. </li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>

<h2 id="Strategy-Integration">Strategy Integration<a class="anchor-link" href="#Strategy-Integration">¶</a></h2><ul>
<li>The agent need not stick to one strategy fully. It may shift on the go as needed. </li>
<li>In CBR, during adaptation, it may find rule based reasoning as most optimal, and so on. Note also how MC provides needed inputs below. </li>
</ul>
<p><img alt="mc_3.gif" src="data:image/gif;base64, "/></p>
<ul>
<li>In MEA, when we hit cul de sac, we used problem reduction which is another method to resolve and then again used MEA for those sub goals. Classic example it is. </li>
</ul>
